2":"1152","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","1084":"1084","1171":"1171","1206":"1206","1139":"1139","1149":"1149","1105":"1105","1135":"1135","1189":"1189","1177":"1177","1209":"1209","1119":"1119","Gamaches, Somme, Picardie, France":"Gamaches, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1121–1184":"1121–1184","1139–1176":"1139–1176","1141–1177":"1141–1177","1135–1189":"1135–1189","1152–1209":"1152–1209","1153–1206":"1153–1206","1171–1231":"1171–1231","1084–Male":"1084–Deceased","1105–1149":"1105–1149","environ 1153":"about 1153","1121":"1121","1231":"1231","1176":"1176","1153":"1153","1152":"1152","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","1084":"1084","1171":"1171","1206":"1206","1139":"1139","1149":"1149","1105":"1105","1135":"1135","1189":"1189","1177":"1177","1209":"1209","1119":"1119","Gamaches, Somme, Picardie, France":"Gamaches, Somme, Picardie, France","Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gamache","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Normand, Adrien, Lucien, Marcel, Aime, Andre, Camille, Fernand, Pierre, Raoul, Aldege.","French: habitational name from (La) Gamache or Gamaches, the name of several places in various parts of France, e.g. in Somme, possibly named from the Celtic elements <i>cam</i> ‘bent, winding’ + <i>apia</i> ‘water’.","History: Nicolas Gamache from Saint-Illiers-la-Ville in Yvelines, France, married Élisabeth-Ursule Cloutier in Château-Richer, QC, in 1676."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alphonse","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of Spanish <i>Alfonso</i>, which is of Germanic (Visigothic) origin. It is probably a compound of <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>funs</i> ‘ready, prompt’. Alternatively, the first element may be <i>ala</i> ‘all’, <i>hadu</i> ‘struggle’, or <i>hild</i> ‘battle’ forms are found to support each derivation, so it is possible that several Visigothic names that were originally distinct have fallen together. The <i>-ph-</i> spelling is the result of classical influences (or classical pretensions).  St Alphonsus  was a 9th-century bishop of Astorga, who spent the last years of his life at the abbey of  St Stephen de Ribas de Sil  in Galicia. <i>Alphonse</i> has been occasionally used in the English-speaking world, especially among West Indians and African Americans. The Latinized form  <b>Alphonsus</b>  has been used in Ireland as an equivalent of the Gaelic name Anluan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alphonse De Gamache was born in 1121, in Gamaches, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Arthus de Gamaches, was 37 and his mother, Aelixe De Foucarmont, was 16. He had at least 3 daughters with Hildegarde De Creseque. He died in 1184, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1121–1184":"1121–1184","1139–1176":"1139–1176","1141–1177":"1141–1177","1135–1189":"1135–1189","1152–1209":"1152–1209","1153–1206":"1153–1206","1171–1231":"1171–1231","1084–Male":"1084–Surnud","1105–1149":"1105–1149","environ 1153":"umbes 1153","1121":"1121","1231":"1231","1176":"1176","1153":"1153","1152":"